docs.abstract: Minutes from the Federal Reserve’s Jan. 30-31 meeting showed policymakers thought that risks of an inflation pickup had “diminished.”
docs.snippet: Minutes from the Federal Reserve’s Jan. 30-31 meeting showed policymakers thought that risks of an inflation pickup had “diminished.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal Reserve officials welcomed a recent inflation slowdown at their last meeting in late January but were intent on proceeding carefully as they tiptoe toward rate cuts, according to minutes from that gathering, which were released on Wednesday.

headline.main: Fed Minutes Show Embrace of Inflation Progress but No Hurry to Cut Rates
headline.print_headline: Fed’s Minutes Show No Rush To Cut Rates

docs.abstract: How negativity bias affects economic perceptions.
docs.snippet: How negativity bias affects economic perceptions.
docs.lead_paragraph: By normal standards, the U.S. economy continues to look very good. Unemployment has now been below 4 percent for 27 months, and inflation remains fairly low, albeit somewhat higher than the Federal Reserve’s target of 2 percent. But if you say that, you get a lot of pushback; some get angry.

headline.main: If It Bleeds It Leads, Inflation Edition

docs.abstract: The president has proposed new barriers to Chinese electric vehicles, steel and other goods in an attempt to protect his manufacturing agenda.
docs.snippet: The president has proposed new barriers to Chinese electric vehicles, steel and other goods in an attempt to protect his manufacturing agenda.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Biden is warning that a new surge of cheap Chinese products poses a threat to American factories. There is little sign of one in official trade data, which show that Chinese steel imports are down sharply from last year and that the gap between what the United States sells to China and what it buys is at a post-pandemic low.

headline.main: Biden Looks to Thwart Surge of Chinese Imports

docs.abstract: The United States will triple its domestic chip manufacturing capacity by 2032, the largest increase in the world, according to a report from the Semiconductor Industry Association.
docs.snippet: The United States will triple its domestic chip manufacturing capacity by 2032, the largest increase in the world, according to a report from the Semiconductor Industry Association.
docs.lead_paragraph: Billions in federal subsidies for semiconductor manufacturers are expected to help reverse a decades-long decline in America’s share of global chip manufacturing.

headline.main: Billions in Chips Grants Are Expected to Fuel Industry Growth, Report Finds
headline.print_headline: Billions in CHIPS Grants Are Expected to Fuel Growth

docs.abstract: The social safety net programs continue to face long-term shortfalls as lawmakers wrestle over changes.
docs.snippet: The social safety net programs continue to face long-term shortfalls as lawmakers wrestle over changes.
docs.lead_paragraph: The financial health of Social Security and Medicare, two of the nation’s most crucial safety net programs, improved this year as a stronger-than-expected economy attracted more workers to the labor market. But the overall financial outlook of the popular programs remained grim.

headline.main: Strong Labor Market Steadied Social Security and Medicare Funds
headline.print_headline: Health of Social Security And Medicare Improves

docs.abstract: For many new college graduates, the job market is bleak even though the unemployment rate is low.
docs.snippet: For many new college graduates, the job market is bleak even though the unemployment rate is low.
docs.lead_paragraph: When I asked new college graduates last month to tell me about their job searches, I got back a ton of heartache. Unanswered applications. Lowered expectations. For some, a sense that college was a waste of time and money.

headline.main: ‘It Feels Like I Am Screaming Into the Void With Each Application’

docs.abstract: Talks in Paris with President Macron produced a call for an “Olympics truce” this summer but no concrete progress on Beijing putting pressure on Russia.
docs.snippet: Talks in Paris with President Macron produced a call for an “Olympics truce” this summer but no concrete progress on Beijing putting pressure on Russia.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Xi Jinping of China, on a two-day visit to France, spoke out firmly against criticism of his country for its close relationship with Russia during the war in Ukraine, saying that “we oppose the crisis being used to cast responsibility on a third country, sully its image and incite a new cold war.”

headline.main: Xi Bristles at Criticism of China Over the War in Ukraine

docs.abstract: The global price of gold has reached its highest levels as Chinese investors and consumers, wary of real estate and stocks, buy the metal at a record pace.

docs.abstract: A cooler-than-expected jobs report for April shifted the tone on Wall Street, rekindling investors’ expectations that the Federal Reserve may cut rates soon.
docs.snippet: A cooler-than-expected jobs report for April shifted the tone on Wall Street, rekindling investors’ expectations that the Federal Reserve may cut rates soon.
docs.lead_paragraph: Just as Wall Street appeared to come to terms with the idea of high interest rates sticking around for longer, a cooler-than-expected jobs report on Friday brought the idea of rate cuts back into the conversation.

headline.main: Jobs Data Revives Wall Street’s Hopes for a Rate Cut
